Claims CLAIMS  What is claimed is: 1 . An orthodontic bracket for receiving an arch wire of orthodontic patients having both primary teeth and permanent teeth, comprising: a pad sized to fit on one of the primary teeth, the pad extending a first distance generally in a longitudinal direction and a second distance generally in a lateral direction, the first distance being greater than the second distance; an eyelet extending from the pad, the eyelet including an aperture defined through the eyelet, the aperture having a central axis oriented transverse to the lateral direction, wherein the aperture is sized to slidingly receive the arch wire. 2. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the pad extends arcuately in the longitudinal direction. 3. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the pad includes a first side and a second side, the eyelet extending from the first side, the second side opposite the first side. 4. The bracket of Claim 3, wherein both the first and second sides extend arcuately in the longitudinal direction. 5. The bracket of Claim 3, wherein the second side of the pad is concave. 6. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the aperture is sized to allow the arch wire to rotate within the aperture through at least 90 degrees of rotation. 7. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the aperture is sized such that the aperture allows free rotation of the arch wire within the aperture. 8. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the aperture is round. 9. The bracket of Claim 8, wherein the arch wire has a rectangular cross section having a diagonal, the aperture has a diameter, and the length of the diameter is greater than the length of the diagonal. 10. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the ratio of the first distance to the second distance is greater than about 1.5. 1 1. The bracket of Claim 1 , wherein the eyelet has a rounded distal end extending away from the pad. 12. An orthodontic bracket for receiving an arch wire of orthodontic patients having both primary teeth and permanent teeth, each of the primary teeth having a facial surface, comprising: a pad sized to fit on and be contained within the facial surface of one of the primary teeth, the pad extending a first distance generally in a longitudinal direction and a second distance generally in a lateral direction, the first distance being greater than the second distance; and 

 an eyelet extending from the pad, the eyelet including a round aperture defined through the eyelet, the round aperture having a central axis oriented transverse to the lateral direction; wherein the aperture is sized to slidingly receive the arch wire and allow free rotation of the arch wire within the aperture. 13. The bracket of Claim 1 1 , wherein: the pad further comprises a first side and a second side; the eyelet extends from the first side; and the second side is arcuate. 14. The bracket of Claim 1 1 , wherein the central axis of the round aperture is substantially parallel with the longitudinal direction. 15. An orthodontic bracket for receiving an arch wire of orthodontic patients having both primary teeth and permanent teeth, each of the primary teeth having a facial surface, the arch wire having a rectangular cross section with a diagonal, the bracket comprising: a pad sized to fit on and be contained within the facial surface of one of the primary teeth, the pad extending a first distance generally in a longitudinal direction and a second distance generally in a lateral direction, the first distance being greater than the second distance, the ratio between the first distance and the second distance being greater than about 1.5; and an eyelet extending from the pad; 

 a round aperture defined through the eyelet, the round aperture having a central axis oriented transverse to the lateral direction, the round aperture having a diameter, the length of the diameter being greater than the length of the diagonal; wherein the aperture is sized to slidingly receive the arch wire and allow free rotation of the arch wire within the aperture. 16. The bracket of the Claim 14, wherein the pad is arcuate along the longitudinal direction.
